            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this sugar calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on <strong>added sugar</strong> – the sugar
                added to drinks and processed foods – because that’s what most
                health guidelines target. It also lets you track
                <em>total</em> sugar if you want to include natural sugar from
                fruit and milk.
              </p>

              <h3>Key conversions</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Grams to teaspoons</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{teaspoons} \approx \dfrac{\text{grams}}{4} \)</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Teaspoons to grams</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{grams} \approx \text{teaspoons} \times 4 \)</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>% Daily Value (US labels)</strong></p>
                <p>By regulation, 50 g added sugar = 100% Daily Value.</p>
                <p>\( \%\text{DV} = \dfrac{\text{grams}}{50} \times 100 \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Guideline ranges used</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>WHO upper limit:</strong> &lt; 10% of daily calories
                  from added sugar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>WHO ideal target:</strong> &lt; 5% of daily calories
                  from added sugar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>US label %DV:</strong> 50 g added sugar = 100% Daily
                  Value.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>For a 2,000‑calorie diet this corresponds to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Upper limit ≈ 50 g (about 12.5 tsp)</li>
                <li>Ideal target ≈ 25 g (about 6 tsp)</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator gives you a
                <strong>percentage of your daily limit</strong>. As a rough
                guide:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>&lt; 50% of ideal target</strong> – very low added
                  sugar intake.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>50–100% of ideal target</strong> – moderate intake for
                  most people.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>100–200% of ideal target</strong> – high intake;
                  consider cutting back.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>&gt; 200% of ideal target</strong> – very high intake;
                  strongly consider changes.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are population‑level guidelines. Individual needs differ,
                especially for people with
                <strong
                  >diabetes, pre‑diabetes, fatty liver disease, or other
                  metabolic conditions</strong
                >.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical ways to reduce added sugar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Swap sugary drinks for water, sparkling water, or unsweetened
                  tea/coffee.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose whole fruit instead of fruit juice or sweetened
                  smoothies.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check labels for added sugar names (syrup, honey, maltose,
                  dextrose, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Pick plain yogurt and add your own fruit instead of flavored
                  varieties.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Gradually reduce sugar in coffee, tea, and home baking so your
                  taste adjusts.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2 id="faq">Medical disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for <strong>general education</strong> and is
                not a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis, or
                treatment. If you have diabetes, pre‑diabetes, or other health
                conditions, follow the guidance of your healthcare provider and
                any individualized nutrition plan you have been given.
              </p>
            </section>
